# frozen_string_literal: true

# Pinned gem closure for the client-side Asciidoctor-PDF WebAssembly build.
#
# Every gem here MUST be pure Ruby (or ship no C extension that survives the wasm32-wasip1
# closure): the engine runs inside the WASI sandbox with no subprocess, no socket, and no native
# extension loading. The wasm build fails closed if any native extension enters the tree.
#
# Native transitive gems (for example bigdecimal, which ships as a compiled default gem) are held
# back below. Prawn's number handling must stay on the pure-Ruby paths; if a code path ever reaches
# a native default gem, prefer a pure-Ruby shim over relaxing this exclusion.

source "https://rubygems.org"

# Core rendering engine and its pure-Ruby companions.
gem "asciidoctor", "~> 2.0"
gem "asciidoctor-pdf", "~> 2.3"

# PDF drawing stack. prawn/ttfunk/pdf-core come in transitively via asciidoctor-pdf; prawn-svg and
# prawn-templates are pulled in explicitly for inline SVG and branded page backgrounds. prawn-svg is
# left unpinned so its version tracks whatever asciidoctor-pdf's own constraint resolves to.
gem "prawn-svg"
gem "prawn-templates", "~> 0.1"

# Source-code syntax highlighting (pure Ruby).
gem "rouge", "~> 4.5"

# Hyphenation dictionaries (pure Ruby, bundled data).
gem "text-hyphen", "~> 1.5"

# Host bridge exposing JavaScript to Ruby inside ruby.wasm.
gem "js", "~> 2.7"

# Inert offline stdlib shims baked into the engine. The rendering closure transitively requires
# net/http (via prawn-svg -> css_parser), which needs the native `socket` and `io/wait` extensions —
# neither exists in the WASI sandbox and neither is in the wasm Ruby build. This local pure-Ruby gem
# provides do-nothing stand-ins so `require 'asciidoctor-pdf'` loads. The pipeline is fully offline, so
# net/http is never actually used; the shims never perform real I/O. Pure Ruby, so it passes the
# no-native-extension gate.
gem "asciidoctor-pdf-wasm-shims", path: "shims/asciidoctor-pdf-wasm-shims"

# ── Intentionally NOT baked into the wasm engine ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Post-convert PDF optimization (the "hexapdf" gem) is deliberately left OUT of this closure. hexapdf
# hard-depends on compiled extensions (an SSL library and a native string scanner) that cannot be
# built for, or loaded inside, the no-compiler WASI sandbox — pulling it in makes the whole engine
# fail to build. PDF optimization is an OPTIONAL capability: the convert pipeline detects that the
# optimizer is absent and simply skips the optimize pass, still emitting a valid PDF. If a pure-Ruby
# optimizer ever becomes viable, re-add it here.
#
# Likewise the native default gem "bigdecimal" is held back — a compiled default gem with no
# pure-Ruby wasm path. Prawn's number handling must stay on its pure-Ruby code paths; prefer a
# pure-Ruby shim over relaxing this exclusion if a path ever reaches it.
# gem "hexapdf", "~> 1.0"   # dropped: drags native openssl + strscan; PDF-optimize left unbaked
# gem "bigdecimal"          # dropped: native compiled default gem
